- **Sixteenth note** â€” Â¼ beat

## Intervals

An **interval** is the distance in pitch between two notes. Intervals are named by number (how many staff positions apart) and quality (major, minor, perfect, augmented, diminished).

| Interval | Semitones | Example | Character |
|----------|-----------|---------|-----------|
| Unison | 0 | Câ€“C | Identity |
| Major 2nd | 2 | Câ€“D | Stepwise motion |
| Major 3rd | 4 | Câ€“E | Bright, consonant |
| Perfect 4th | 5 | Câ€“F | Open, stable |
| Perfect 5th | 7 | Câ€“G | Most consonant after octave |
| Major 6th | 9 | Câ€“A | Warm, lyrical |
| Major 7th | 11 | Câ€“B | Tense, leading |
| Octave | 12 | Câ€“C | Consonant, completion |

The **tritone** (6 semitones, e.g., Câ€“Fâ™¯) was called *diabolus in musica* ("the devil in music") by medieval theorists because of its extreme dissonance. Its resolution is a key driver of harmonic tension in Western music.

## Harmony and Chords

A **chord** is three or more pitches sounded simultaneously. The most fundamental chord is the **triad**, built by stacking two intervals of a third above a **root** note.

